{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"What technology can we really apply to reducing global poverty?"},{"time":6000,"text":"And what I found was quite surprising."},{"time":10000,"text":"We started looking at things like death rates in the 20th century,"},{"time":13000,"text":"and how they'd been improved, and very simple things turned out."},{"time":16000,"text":"You'd think maybe antibiotics made more difference than clean water,"},{"time":19000,"text":"but it's actually the opposite."},{"time":22000,"text":"And so very simple things -- off-the-shelf technologies"},{"time":25000,"text":"that we could easily find on the then-early Web --"},{"time":30000,"text":"would clearly make a huge difference to that problem."}]},{"cues":[{"time":35000,"text":"But I also, in looking at more powerful technologies"},{"time":39000,"text":"and nanotechnology and genetic engineering and other new emerging"},{"time":44000,"text":"kind of digital technologies, became very concerned"},{"time":48000,"text":"about the potential for abuse."},{"time":52000,"text":"If you think about it, in history, a long, long time ago"},{"time":57000,"text":"we dealt with the problem of an individual abusing another individual."},{"time":60000,"text":"We came up with something -- the Ten Commandments: Thou shalt not kill."},{"time":63000,"text":"That's a, kind of a one-on-one thing."},{"time":65000,"text":"We organized into cities. We had many people."},{"time":69000,"text":"And to keep the many from tyrannizing the one,"},{"time":73000,"text":"we came up with concepts like individual liberty."},{"time":77000,"text":"And then, to have to deal with large groups,"},{"time":78000,"text":"say, at the nation-state level,"},{"time":81000,"text":"and we had to have mutual non-aggression,"},{"time":83000,"text":"or through a series of conflicts, we eventually came to"},{"time":87000,"text":"a rough international bargain to largely keep the peace."}]},{"cues":[{"time":93000,"text":"But now we have a new situation, really what people call"},{"time":98000,"text":"an asymmetric situation, where technology is so powerful"},{"time":101000,"text":"that it extends beyond a nation-state."},{"time":105000,"text":"It's not the nation-states that have potential access"},{"time":108000,"text":"to mass destruction, but individuals."},{"time":113000,"text":"And this is a consequence of the fact that these new technologies tend to be digital."},{"time":118000,"text":"We saw genome sequences."},{"time":122000,"text":"You can download the gene sequences"},{"time":123000,"text":"of pathogens off the Internet if you want to,"},{"time":127000,"text":"and clearly someone recently -- I saw in a science magazine --"},{"time":132000,"text":"they said, well, the 1918 flu is too dangerous to FedEx around."},{"time":137000,"text":"If people want to use it in their labs for working on research,"},{"time":140000,"text":"just reconstruct it yourself,"},{"time":143000,"text":"because, you know, it might break in FedEx."},{"time":147000,"text":"So that this is possible to do this is not deniable."}]},{"cues":[{"time":152000,"text":"So individuals in small groups super-empowered by access to these"},{"time":157000,"text":"kinds of self-replicating technologies, whether it be biological"},{"time":162000,"text":"or other, are clearly a danger in our world."},{"time":165000,"text":"And the danger is that they can cause roughly what's a pandemic."},{"time":169000,"text":"And we really don't have experience with pandemics,"},{"time":172000,"text":"and we're also not very good as a society at acting"},{"time":175000,"text":"to things we don't have direct and sort of gut-level experience with."},{"time":179000,"text":"So it's not in our nature to pre-act."},{"time":183000,"text":"And in this case, piling on more technology doesn't solve the problem,"},{"time":188000,"text":"because it only super-empowers people more."}]},{"cues":[{"time":191000,"text":"So the solution has to be, as people like Russell and Einstein"},{"time":195000,"text":"and others imagine in a conversation that existed"},{"time":197000,"text":"in a much stronger form, I think, early in the 20th century,"},{"time":201000,"text":"that the solution had to be not just the head but the heart."},{"time":204000,"text":"You know, public policy and moral progress."},{"time":209000,"text":"The bargain that gives us civilization is a bargain to not use power."},{"time":215000,"text":"We get our individual rights by society protecting us from others"},{"time":218000,"text":"not doing everything they can do but largely doing only what is legal."},{"time":223000,"text":"And so to limit the danger of these new things, we have to limit,"},{"time":228000,"text":"ultimately, the ability of individuals"},{"time":230000,"text":"to have access, essentially, to pandemic power."},{"time":233000,"text":"We also have to have sensible defense, because no limitation"},{"time":237000,"text":"is going to prevent a crazy person from doing something."},{"time":240000,"text":"And you know, and the troubling thing is that"},{"time":242000,"text":"it's much easier to do something bad than to defend"},{"time":244000,"text":"against all possible bad things,"},{"time":246000,"text":"so the offensive uses really have an asymmetric advantage."}]},{"cues":[{"time":250000,"text":"So these are the kind of thoughts I was thinking in 1999 and 2000,"},{"time":254000,"text":"and my friends told me I was getting really depressed,"},{"time":256000,"text":"and they were really worried about me."},{"time":258000,"text":"And then I signed a book contract to write more gloomy thoughts about this"},{"time":261000,"text":"and moved into a hotel room in New York"},{"time":263000,"text":"with one room full of books on the Plague,"},{"time":267000,"text":"and you know, nuclear bombs exploding in New York"},{"time":270000,"text":"where I would be within the circle, and so on."},{"time":273000,"text":"And then I was there on September 11th,"},{"time":277000,"text":"and I stood in the streets with everyone."},{"time":278000,"text":"And it was quite an experience to be there."},{"time":280000,"text":"I got up the next morning and walked out of the city,"},{"time":283000,"text":"and all the sanitation trucks were parked on Houston Street"},{"time":286000,"text":"and ready to go down and start taking the rubble away."},{"time":288000,"text":"And I walked down the middle, up to the train station,"},{"time":290000,"text":"and everything below 14th Street was closed."},{"time":293000,"text":"It was quite a compelling experience, but not really, I suppose,"},{"time":297000,"text":"a surprise to someone who'd had his room full of the books."},{"time":300000,"text":"It was always a surprise that it happened then and there,"},{"time":304000,"text":"but it wasn't a surprise that it happened at all."}]},{"cues":[{"time":308000,"text":"And everyone then started writing about this."},{"time":310000,"text":"Thousands of people started writing about this."},{"time":311000,"text":"And I eventually abandoned the book, and then Chris called me"},{"time":313000,"text":"to talk at the conference. I really don't talk about this anymore"},{"time":316000,"text":"because, you know, there's enough frustrating and depressing things going on."},{"time":321000,"text":"But I agreed to come and say a few things about this."},{"time":324000,"text":"And I would say that we can't give up the rule of law"},{"time":327000,"text":"to fight an asymmetric threat, which is what we seem to be doing"},{"time":331000,"text":"because of the present, the people that are in power,"},{"time":336000,"text":"because that's to give up the thing that makes civilization."},{"time":341000,"text":"And we can't fight the threat in the kind of stupid way we're doing,"},{"time":344000,"text":"because a million-dollar act"},{"time":346000,"text":"causes a billion dollars of damage, causes a trillion dollar response"},{"time":349000,"text":"which is largely ineffective and arguably, probably almost certainly,"},{"time":352000,"text":"has made the problem worse."},{"time":354000,"text":"So we can't fight the thing with a million-to-one cost,"},{"time":359000,"text":"one-to-a-million cost-benefit ratio."}]},{"cues":[{"time":366000,"text":"So after giving up on the book -- and I had the great honor"},{"time":371000,"text":"to be able to join Kleiner Perkins about a year ago,"},{"time":375000,"text":"and to work through venture capital on the innovative side,"},{"time":382000,"text":"and to try to find some innovations that could address what I saw as"},{"time":386000,"text":"some of these big problems."},{"time":388000,"text":"Things where, you know, a factor of 10 difference"},{"time":391000,"text":"can make a factor of 1,000 difference in the outcome."},{"time":395000,"text":"I've been amazed in the last year at the incredible quality"},{"time":398000,"text":"and excitement of the innovations that have come across my desk."},{"time":403000,"text":"It's overwhelming at times. I'm very thankful for Google and Wikipedia"},{"time":406000,"text":"so I can understand at least a little of what people are talking about"},{"time":410000,"text":"who come through the doors."}]},{"cues":[{"time":412000,"text":"But I wanted to share with you three areas"},{"time":415000,"text":"that I'm particularly excited about and that relate to the problems"},{"time":418000,"text":"that I was talking about in the Wired article."},{"time":423000,"text":"The first is this whole area of education,"},{"time":425000,"text":"and it really relates to what Nicholas was talking about with a $100 computer."},{"time":429000,"text":"And that is to say that there's a lot of legs left in Moore's Law."},{"time":433000,"text":"The most advanced transistors today are at 65 nanometers,"},{"time":437000,"text":"and we've seen, and I've had the pleasure to invest"},{"time":440000,"text":"in, companies that give me great confidence that we'll extend Moore's Law"},{"time":446000,"text":"all the way down to roughly the 10 nanometer scale."},{"time":449000,"text":"Another factor of, say, six in dimensional reduction,"},{"time":455000,"text":"which should give us about another factor of 100 in raw improvement"},{"time":460000,"text":"in what the chips can do. And so, to put that in practical terms,"},{"time":465000,"text":"if something costs about 1,000 dollars today,"},{"time":469000,"text":"say, the best personal computer you can buy, that might be its cost,"},{"time":474000,"text":"I think we can have that in 2020 for 10 dollars. Okay?"},{"time":480000,"text":"Now, just imagine what that $100 computer will be in 2020"},{"time":485000,"text":"as a tool for education."}]},{"cues":[{"time":487000,"text":"I think the challenge for us is --"},{"time":489000,"text":"I'm very certain that that will happen, the challenge is,"},{"time":491000,"text":"will we develop the kind of educational tools and things with the net"},{"time":496000,"text":"to let us take advantage of that device?"},{"time":499000,"text":"I'd argue today that we have incredibly powerful computers,"},{"time":503000,"text":"but we don't have very good software for them."},{"time":505000,"text":"And it's only in retrospect, after the better software comes along,"},{"time":508000,"text":"and you take it and you run it on a ten-year-old machine, you say,"},{"time":510000,"text":"God, the machine was that fast?"},{"time":512000,"text":"I remember when they took the Apple Mac interface"},{"time":514000,"text":"and they put it back on the Apple II."},{"time":517000,"text":"The Apple II was perfectly capable of running that kind of interface,"},{"time":520000,"text":"we just didn't know how to do it at the time."},{"time":523000,"text":"So given that we know and should believe --"},{"time":525000,"text":"because Moore's Law's been, like, a constant,"},{"time":528000,"text":"I mean, it's just been very predictable progress"},{"time":531000,"text":"over the last 40 years or whatever."},{"time":534000,"text":"We can know what the computers are going to be like in 2020."},{"time":538000,"text":"It's great that we have initiatives to say,"},{"time":540000,"text":"let's go create the education and educate people in the world,"},{"time":543000,"text":"because that's a great force for peace."},{"time":545000,"text":"And we can give everyone in the world a $100 computer"},{"time":548000,"text":"or a $10 computer in the next 15 years."}]},{"cues":[{"time":553000,"text":"The second area that I'm focusing on is the environmental problem,"},{"time":558000,"text":"because that's clearly going to put a lot of pressure on this world."},{"time":562000,"text":"We'll hear a lot more about that from Al Gore very shortly."},{"time":566000,"text":"The thing that we see as the kind of Moore's Law trend"},{"time":569000,"text":"that's driving improvement in our ability to address"},{"time":572000,"text":"the environmental problem is new materials."},{"time":576000,"text":"We have a challenge, because the urban population is growing"},{"time":580000,"text":"in this century from two billion to six billion"},{"time":583000,"text":"in a very short amount of time. People are moving to the cities."},{"time":585000,"text":"They all need clean water, they need energy, they need transportation,"},{"time":588000,"text":"and we want them to develop in a green way."},{"time":592000,"text":"We're reasonably efficient in the industrial sectors."},{"time":594000,"text":"We've made improvements in energy and resource efficiency,"},{"time":597000,"text":"but the consumer sector, especially in America, is very inefficient."},{"time":601000,"text":"But these new materials bring such incredible innovations"},{"time":605000,"text":"that there's a strong basis for hope that these things"},{"time":609000,"text":"will be so profitable that they can be brought to the market."}]},{"cues":[{"time":611000,"text":"And I want to give you a specific example of a new material"},{"time":614000,"text":"that was discovered 15 years ago."},{"time":617000,"text":"If we take carbon nanotubes, you know, Iijima discovered them in 1991,"},{"time":622000,"text":"they just have incredible properties."},{"time":624000,"text":"And these are the kinds of things we're going to discover"},{"time":625000,"text":"as we start to engineer at the nano scale."},{"time":628000,"text":"Their strength: they're almost the strongest material,"},{"time":631000,"text":"tensile strength material known."},{"time":634000,"text":"They're very, very stiff. They stretch very, very little.\n"},{"time":639000,"text":"In two dimensions, if you make, like, a fabric out of them,"},{"time":642000,"text":"they're 30 times stronger than Kevlar."},{"time":645000,"text":"And if you make a three-dimensional structure, like a buckyball,"},{"time":648000,"text":"they have all sorts of incredible properties."},{"time":650000,"text":"If you shoot a particle at them and knock a hole in them,"},{"time":653000,"text":"they repair themselves; they go zip and they repair the hole"},{"time":656000,"text":"in femtoseconds, which is not -- is really quick."},{"time":659000,"text":"(Laughter)"},{"time":662000,"text":"If you shine a light on them, they produce electricity."},{"time":666000,"text":"In fact, if you flash them with a camera they catch on fire."},{"time":669000,"text":"If you put electricity on them, they emit light."},{"time":673000,"text":"If you run current through them, you can run 1,000 times more current"},{"time":676000,"text":"through one of these than through a piece of metal."},{"time":680000,"text":"You can make both p- and n-type semiconductors,"},{"time":683000,"text":"which means you can make transistors out of them."},{"time":685000,"text":"They conduct heat along their length but not across --"},{"time":688000,"text":"well, there is no width, but not in the other direction"},{"time":690000,"text":"if you stack them up; that's a property of carbon fiber also."},{"time":696000,"text":"If you put particles in them, and they go shooting out the tip --"},{"time":699000,"text":"they're like miniature linear accelerators or electron guns."},{"time":702000,"text":"The inside of the nanotubes is so small --"},{"time":705000,"text":"the smallest ones are 0.7 nanometers --"},{"time":707000,"text":"that it's basically a quantum world."},{"time":709000,"text":"It's a strange place inside a nanotube."}]},{"cues":[{"time":712000,"text":"And so we begin to see, and we've seen business plans already,"},{"time":715000,"text":"where the kind of things Lisa Randall's talking about are in there."},{"time":718000,"text":"I had one business plan where I was trying to learn more about"},{"time":720000,"text":"Witten's cosmic dimension strings to try to understand"},{"time":723000,"text":"what the phenomenon was going on in this proposed nanomaterial."},{"time":726000,"text":"So inside of a nanotube, we're really at the limit here."},{"time":732000,"text":"So what we see is with these and other new materials"},{"time":736000,"text":"that we can do things with different properties -- lighter, stronger --"},{"time":740000,"text":"and apply these new materials to the environmental problems."},{"time":746000,"text":"New materials that can make water,"},{"time":747000,"text":"new materials that can make fuel cells work better,"},{"time":749000,"text":"new materials that catalyze chemical reactions,"},{"time":753000,"text":"that cut pollution and so on."},{"time":756000,"text":"Ethanol -- new ways of making ethanol."},{"time":759000,"text":"New ways of making electric transportation."},{"time":762000,"text":"The whole green dream -- because it can be profitable."},{"time":766000,"text":"And we've dedicated -- we've just raised a new fund,"},{"time":768000,"text":"we dedicated 100 million dollars to these kinds of investments."},{"time":771000,"text":"We believe that Genentech, the Compaq, the Lotus, the Sun,"},{"time":775000,"text":"the Netscape, the Amazon, the Google in these fields"},{"time":779000,"text":"are yet to be found, because this materials revolution"},{"time":782000,"text":"will drive these things forward."}]},{"cues":[{"time":786000,"text":"The third area that we're working on,"},{"time":788000,"text":"and we just announced last week -- we were all in New York."},{"time":792000,"text":"We raised 200 million dollars in a specialty fund"},{"time":798000,"text":"to work on a pandemic in biodefense."},{"time":802000,"text":"And to give you an idea of the last fund that Kleiner raised"},{"time":805000,"text":"was a $400 million fund, so this for us is a very substantial fund."},{"time":810000,"text":"And what we did, over the last few months -- well, a few months ago,"},{"time":814000,"text":"Ray Kurzweil and I wrote an op-ed in the New York Times"},{"time":817000,"text":"about how publishing the 1918 genome was very dangerous."},{"time":820000,"text":"And John Doerr and Brook and others got concerned, [unclear],"},{"time":824000,"text":"and we started looking around at what the world was doing"},{"time":828000,"text":"about being prepared for a pandemic. And we saw a lot of gaps."}]},{"cues":[{"time":833000,"text":"And so we asked ourselves, you know, can we find innovative things"},{"time":837000,"text":"that will go fill these gaps? And Brooks told me in a break here,"},{"time":841000,"text":"he said he's found so much stuff he can't sleep,"},{"time":843000,"text":"because there's so many great technologies out there,"},{"time":846000,"text":"we're essentially buried. And we need them, you know."},{"time":849000,"text":"We have one antiviral that people are talking about stockpiling"},{"time":852000,"text":"that still works, roughly. That's Tamiflu."},{"time":855000,"text":"But Tamiflu -- the virus is resistant. It is resistant to Tamiflu."},{"time":860000,"text":"We've discovered with AIDS we need cocktails to work well"},{"time":864000,"text":"so that the viral resistance -- we need several anti-virals."},{"time":867000,"text":"We need better surveillance."},{"time":869000,"text":"We need networks that can find out what's going on."},{"time":872000,"text":"We need rapid diagnostics so that we can tell if somebody has"},{"time":876000,"text":"a strain of flu which we have only identified very recently."},{"time":880000,"text":"We've got to be able to make the rapid diagnostics quickly."},{"time":882000,"text":"We need new anti-virals and cocktails. We need new kinds of vaccines."},{"time":885000,"text":"Vaccines that are broad spectrum."},{"time":887000,"text":"Vaccines that we can manufacture quickly."},{"time":891000,"text":"Cocktails, more polyvalent vaccines."},{"time":893000,"text":"You normally get a trivalent vaccine against three possible strains."},{"time":896000,"text":"We need -- we don't know where this thing is going."},{"time":899000,"text":"We believe that if we could fill these 10 gaps,"},{"time":902000,"text":"we have a chance to help really reduce the risk of a pandemic."},{"time":908000,"text":"And the difference between a normal flu season and a pandemic"},{"time":912000,"text":"is about a factor of 1,000 in deaths"},{"time":915000,"text":"and certainly enormous economic impact."},{"time":918000,"text":"So we're very excited because we think we can fund 10,"},{"time":921000,"text":"or speed up 10 projects and see them come to market"},{"time":925000,"text":"in the next couple years that will address this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":928000,"text":"So if we can address, use technology, help address education,"},{"time":931000,"text":"help address the environment, help address the pandemic,"},{"time":934000,"text":"does that solve the larger problem that I was talking about"},{"time":938000,"text":"in the Wired article? And I'm afraid the answer is really no,"},{"time":943000,"text":"because you can't solve a problem with the management of technology"},{"time":947000,"text":"with more technology."},{"time":950000,"text":"If we let an unlimited amount of power loose, then we will --"},{"time":955000,"text":"a very small number of people will be able to abuse it."},{"time":957000,"text":"We can't fight at a million-to-one disadvantage."},{"time":961000,"text":"So what we need to do is, we need better policy."},{"time":964000,"text":"And for example, some things we could do"},{"time":967000,"text":"that would be policy solutions which are not really in the political air right now"},{"time":971000,"text":"but perhaps with the change of administration would be -- use markets."}]},{"cues":[{"time":975000,"text":"Markets are a very strong force."},{"time":977000,"text":"For example, rather than trying to regulate away problems,"},{"time":980000,"text":"which probably won't work, if we could price"},{"time":982000,"text":"into the cost of doing business, the cost of catastrophe,"},{"time":987000,"text":"so that people who are doing things that had a higher cost of catastrophe"},{"time":990000,"text":"would have to take insurance against that risk."},{"time":993000,"text":"So if you wanted to put a drug on the market you could put it on."},{"time":995000,"text":"But it wouldn't have to be approved by regulators;"},{"time":997000,"text":"you'd have to convince an actuary that it would be safe."},{"time":1001000,"text":"And if you apply the notion of insurance more broadly,"},{"time":1004000,"text":"you can use a more powerful force, a market force,"},{"time":1007000,"text":"to provide feedback."},{"time":1009000,"text":"How could you keep the law?"},{"time":1010000,"text":"I think the law would be a really good thing to keep."},{"time":1012000,"text":"Well, you have to hold people accountable."},{"time":1014000,"text":"The law requires accountability."},{"time":1016000,"text":"Today scientists, technologists, businessmen, engineers"},{"time":1019000,"text":"don't have any personal responsibility"},{"time":1021000,"text":"for the consequences of their actions."},{"time":1023000,"text":"So if you tie that -- you have to tie that back with the law."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1027000,"text":"And finally, I think we have to do something that's not really --"},{"time":1031000,"text":"it's almost unacceptable to say this -- which,"},{"time":1032000,"text":"we have to begin to design the future."},{"time":1035000,"text":"We can't pick the future, but we can steer the future."},{"time":1039000,"text":"Our investment in trying to prevent pandemic flu"},{"time":1041000,"text":"is affecting the distribution of possible outcomes."},{"time":1045000,"text":"We may not be able to stop it, but the likelihood"},{"time":1047000,"text":"that it will get past us is lower if we focus on that problem."},{"time":1051000,"text":"So we can design the future if we choose what kind of things"},{"time":1055000,"text":"we want to have happen and not have happen,"},{"time":1058000,"text":"and steer us to a lower-risk place."},{"time":1061000,"text":"Vice President Gore will talk about how we could steer the climate trajectory"},{"time":1067000,"text":"into a lower probability of catastrophic risk."}]},{"cues":[{"time":1070000,"text":"But above all, what we have to do is we have to help the good guys,"},{"time":1073000,"text":"the people on the defensive side,"},{"time":1075000,"text":"have an advantage over the people who want to abuse things."},{"time":1079000,"text":"And what we have to do to do that"},{"time":1081000,"text":"is we have to limit access to certain information."},{"time":1084000,"text":"And growing up as we have, and holding very high"},{"time":1087000,"text":"the value of free speech, this is a hard thing for us to accept --"},{"time":1091000,"text":"for all of us to accept."},{"time":1092000,"text":"It's especially hard for the scientists to accept who still remember,"},{"time":1097000,"text":"you know, Galileo essentially locked up,"},{"time":1099000,"text":"and who are still fighting this battle against the church."},{"time":1103000,"text":"But that's the price of having a civilization."},{"time":1108000,"text":"The price of retaining the rule of law"},{"time":1110000,"text":"is to limit the access to the great and kind of unbridled power."},{"time":1115000,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":1116000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}